Predicting the Super Bowl
¶

Jason Ramsland

Introduction
¶

The Super Bowl is the final championship game of the National Football League, where the AFC champions face off against the NFC champions. It is the biggest Televised event in the United States every year. More information on the Super bowl can be found here. In this tutorial, we will explore Super Bowl data dating back to the first Super Bowl in 1967, to the most recent one this past year in 2022. The game has changed jurassicly over the years, from new rules being enforced to new styles of play and coaching philosophies, NFL games of today look much different than it did back in 1967. These changes provide us with motivation to see how these instances of change have affected Super Bowl performances. From this tutorial, football fans will gain new insights on current trends that exist in the sport they love, and non-football fans will learn why modern day football might be more exciting than it has ever been before.

We will start by importing a dataset found here, which includes the date, location (stadium, city, and state), winning team, losing team, points scored by both teams, and the Super bowl number.

This plot is much easier to read. We can see that there is only one instance of a special teams player winning MVP, and this was in 1997. We also see that although offensive players have generally dominated winning MVP, there is a fairly even scattering of defensive players who have won it over the years, and the most recent occurrence of this was in 2016 when linebacker Von Miller won it. I was expecting to see correlation between low scoring games leading to defensive players winning MVP, and high scoring games leading to offensive players winning MVP. However, we can see that this is not the case considering that 2003 was a high scoring game but a defensive player won MVP, and alternatively 2019 was a low scoring game and an offensive player won MVP.

Since we were not able to find correlation between points scored and MVP position, lets instead look at the point differential over the years.

In [302]:
import numpy as np

dates=[]
diff=[]
for i in range (0,56): # Calculate year and differential for each row
    dates.append(2022-i)
    diff.append(df.iloc[i,3] - df.iloc[i,5])
x = np.array(dates)
y = np.array(diff)
a, b = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18,7))
plt.scatter(x, y, color='red')
# Regression line
plt.plot(x, a*x+b, color='blue', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
ax.set_xlabel('Year')
ax.set_ylabel('Point Difference')
ax.set_title('Point Difference over the Years')
plt.show()

We can see that there is some negative correlation of point differential over time. However, considering there are several outliers around 1990, lets break up this plot into 5 subplots to get a better understanding on how the point differential has changed over time.

Hypothesis Testing
¶

The plots we have looked at thus far have shown some correlation between point differential and time, so lets present the hypothesis that as years increase, point differential will decrease. Therefore, the null hypothesis is that there is no correlation between point differential and time.

To test our hypothesis we will create a linear regression model that predicts the change in point differential per year. We will start by including data from all the years in our dataset (1967 - 2022).

In [305]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as sm
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

table = pd.DataFrame({'year':dates,'diff':diff})

# Variables
X = np.array(table['year']).reshape(-1, 1)
Y = np.array(table['diff']).reshape(-1, 1)

reg = LinearRegression().fit(X,Y)
print(reg.coef_[0]) # slope
result = sm.ols(formula="diff ~ year", data=table).fit()
result.summary()

Our linear regression model predicts a 0.1215 decrease in point differential per year. However our p-value is greater than 5%, so we cannot reject the null hypothesis. We know that the only subplot of our data that produced a positive regression line was the time period from 1979 to 1989, so lets make a linear regression model that encompasses the time period from 1989 to 2022.

This model predicts a 0.8233 decrease in point differential per year. Our p-value is less than 5%, so we reject the null hypothesis, thus accepting our alternate hypothesis that point differential will decrease over time.

(Note that our linear regression models can only be used to predict Super Bowl point differentials in the near future, because the actual point differential will never drop below 1, and a decrease of 0.8233 every year would eventually result in a differential <1 which is impossible)

Insights
¶

The main insight we learned was that the scores between the winner and the loser of the Superbowl have become gradually closer since 1990. But why? As we discussed in the introduction, there have been many changes that have taken place in the NFL since its inaugural Super Bowl. One significant change was the introduction of the salary cap in 1994. The salary cap sets a limit on the amount of money a team can spend on their roster during a given season. The purpose of this is to keep the talent level of teams relatively equal, so that there is no one team that can go on a spending spree and buy out all of the star players. Is this the primary cause of the Super Bowl point differential decreasing since the 1990s? I think yes. The salary cap prevents any team from becoming "too good," therefore the AFC championship team and the NFC championship team will produce a more competitive matchup in their Super Bowl meeting, thus creating closer scored games. However, we would need to do further testing to test the validity of this hypothesis.

One interesting resource reguarding the NFL salary cap is spotrac, which keeps track of NFL player salaries and their cap hit, meaning the percentage of the salary cap that the given player's salary consumes. Unfortunately, we are unable to collect most of this data because it lies behind a paywall. Hopefully in the future we will be able to access this data and perform data science on it to determine the true impact of the salary cap on NFL and Super Bowl scoring.
